text:
This was a fun stream, I really enjoyed playing that game ^ ^  As someone new to the game, it is so good to start fresh and learn this way, because new people who join already established groups have no appreciation for what it takes to get there.  I hope you will try the game again, since once you learn the basics, then wild dinosaurs no longer seem like a threat, and even as a brand new character you will have advance without issue.

Some general tips:
  Food meter depletes slowly, but is also used to refill stamina and health meters, so if you avoid taking damage and sprinting everywhere, it will last much longer.
  Pickaxe is good for meat, flint, and thatch;  Axe is good for skin, rocks, and wood.  Punching hurts you too.
  Narco berries (black) will put things to sleep, and you can force feed them to unconscious dinos, Stim berries (white) refill some stamina while dehydrating you, the rest of the berries are good for eating and feeding to dinos to tame them (Mejo berries, purple, are the best berry for taming).
  For knocking out dinos:  The club is a PvP weapon, not good for dinos, the first good item is the slingshot, headshots do more damage and knock them out faster.  For anything that runs away, use a bola.  You can walk up to a Phiomia's head, bola it, then headshot it multiple times with the slingshot to knock it out before it has time to run away.
  I recommend always carrying a few bolas on you, since when a raptor or other smallish predator finds you, you can lock them in place and kill them safely.
  Dino inventories are like a fridge, store food on them so it lasts longer.  Later you will get access to the preserving bin, which will be your main fridge for the game until endgame when you have electricity.
  When babies are born, they last for a while before dying while unclaimed, giving you some time to grab food from inventories.  As soon as they are claimed, put food in their inventory before claiming the next one.  Only have to hand feed in baby form, when adolescent they can eat from a feeding trough (if you have one).

text:
Looks like ARK Start-Area is more peaceful than back then, when i played xD 
They implemented so many new Animals since i played. But i recognize a few from the Update-Newsletter.
I wonder if ol' Spino is still in his old Spawn place^^

Edit: Yeah, looks like Spino is still in the Start-Area.
Kill any Compy you see..... they act friendly as long they are few.... they hunt in Packs.
This 150m range is annoying :o You should check if that can be changed. The Isle is FAR to big to explore it with such limited Range.

I stopped playing before they changed the nice Metal-Spawn into an active Vulcano. If i ever play again, i will have to start from scratch. I miss my Birds. Once i made an error and my favorite Bird died while protecting me. I panicked, closed the Game and didnt touched it for Days. Was very happy that the Game didnt saved after it happened and the Game doesnt recreated the dangerous situation when i logged in again. I could save Birdie :3

Edit2: You can and absolutely should tell your little friends to stay passiv and NOT defend you. Its mean to tell it in this Way, but i advice you to read the Options and commands within the Game to prevent another Tragedy.
Alternatively..... build Walls/Fences to keep neutral Animals out of your Property.

To give a basic overview:
Most smaller herbivores are skittish, they will flee if you hit them. Some bigger herbivores flee too, like the Parasaurus. Armed herbivores and large herbivores WILL punish you if you hit them. If they have Hearts, it means they have a Partner and Partners will always defend each other, thats why both Triceratops attacked.
If you find an Egg near wild Animals: DO. NOT. TOUCH. IT!!! The Parents WILL chase you, they WILL kill you! This counts for all Animals, even the Skittish.

If you both give ARK a second Chance, i would advice you to take the Breeding slowly. First is the building of a Base/Home. Secure Food. Dodos give you Eggs, so you can have some, but dont force them to Breed. Before you start Breeding, make sure, they are safe and sound. Build Walls and Fences to keep annoying Neighbors out. Atleast wooden Walls, Thatch walls are fragile.
Its a lot of work, but its for the safety of your future Dodo-Army ;) Maybe build a Barn for your small Chickens^^ ARK gives you alot of options for building.
Whistle every new Animal to stay passive, unless you declare this specific one to be your Bodyguard.  Unless youre very careful, you will lose close Friends from time to time in Ark :(
Aggressive Animals come in all sizes, from Ants to animals bigger than the Spino. Some hunt alone, others in Packs.
The Beach is relatively safe, aslong Spinos or Raptors doesnt decide to take a stroll :x

Good Luck Gura and Mumei ^_^
We all had to learn in the Beginning and this Island isnt a Vacation spot....... unless you change it into one :)

text:
The reason that passive tamed Lystrosaurus was bleeding was because it wasn't eating enough. After you feed a dino for the first time they stop eating completely unless you give them food even while they're not completely tamed. Don't think you guys figured that out so I thought I'd write it here. You have to continually keep feeding them every time it's available or else they will die. I wasn't watching your stream but that dino also eats Mejoberries. Narcoberries don't raise their hunger(they are used to increase unconscious time) and stimberries make them thirsty but wake them up when they're unconscious. Mejoberries are usually the only berry you want to use to tame herbivores.

Also the reason the Triceratops was red was because the Spinosaurus(the big alligator looking thing with the giant dorsal fin) makes certain dinos stronger that are around it.

Also the host distance thing will get EXTREMELY annoying the more you progress. I literally had to buy a server to play with my friend because it got so annoying when I didn't have a good computer to increase the distance much.
